<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900727-0028</DOCNO><DOCID>900727-0028.</DOCID><HL>   What's News --   Business and Finance</HL><DATE>07/27/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1</SO><LP>   GM AND FORD POSTED sharply lower second-quarter earnings,reflecting hard times in the U.S. market and economic unrestin Brazil. Ford's profit tumbled 45% while GM reported a 38%decline. The remainder of the year could be difficult, too,amid weak demand in the U.S. and competition from Japan.   ---</LP><TEXT>   A former Drexel official, Peter Ackerman, has become thesubject of a new government probe into possible pricemanipulation, according to people familiar with theinvestigation. Mr. Ackerman was once top deputy to ex-junkbond king Michael Milken.   ---   A plan to propose higher taxes on alcoholic beverages andlimits on deductions for state and local taxes wastentatively agreed to by the administration and congressionalRepublicans, according to people close to the plan. Butsupport was shaky.   ---   OPEC ministers neared agreement on a new productionceiling intended to reduce the current world oil glut andpush up crude oil prices.   ---   Growing real estate problems in California are hurtinglenders. Coast Savings Financial reported a $28.7 millionsecond-quarter loss, following losses by CalFed and HomeFed.   ---   GE was ordered to pay a $10 million criminal fine andagreed to pay $20 million in civil penalties in connectionwith fraudulent defense contract billings to the U.S. Army.   ---   Sallie Mae has proposed taking over the portfolio of atroubled student-loan guarantor, a move that would greatlyexpand its influence in the education financing field.   ---   House and Senate conferees agreed on comprehensiveoil-spill legislation that would end a 16-year congressionalstalemate on the issue.   ---   Cigarette package warnings don't protect tobacco makersfrom product liability lawsuits, New Jersey's Supreme Courtruled. The decision opens the door for a review of the issueby the U.S. Supreme Court.   ---   A House panel voted to reimpose rate regulation on basiccable-TV service. The measure also would benefit fledglingcompetitors of cable.   ---   UAL's profit rose slightly in the second quarter, aided bythe sale of aircraft. But Midway Airlines recorded a heftyloss for the period.   ---   Westinghouse agreed to acquire Knoll International,doubling the size of its office-furniture business.   ---   Eli Lilly was named in a second lawsuit charging that itspopular new antidepressant drug Prozac can cause violent anddestructive behavior. Lilly's stock fell $4.375 to $79.625.   ---   The Senate embraced a proposal to revamp the federalcrop-insurance program and cover its underwriting losses,putting senators at odds with the House's intention toscuttle the long-troubled program.   ---   Microsoft is planning a costly campaign to win a biggerpiece of the market for software that ties together personalcomputers. The effort will cost the company up to $50million.   ---   Continental Bank moved closer to full private ownership asthe FDIC approved plans to sell a 26% stake in the Chicagobanking concern.   ---   Markets --   Stocks: Volume 155,040,000 shares. Dow Jones industrials2920.79, off 10.15; transportation 1142.15, up 0.54;utilities 203.16, up 0.51.   Bonds: Shearson Lehman Hutton Treasury index 3438.01, up2.96.   Commodities: Dow Jones futures index 132.26, up 0.65; spotindex 132.81, up 0.51.   Dollar: 150.37 yen, up 0.48; 1.6245 marks, off 0.0005.</TEXT></DOC>